}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-6.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The two 'companions' are running, but not as quickly as the souls who precede them, \softline
while Virgil considers his previous inappropriate behavior and Dante his own (as we shall learn in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.7-9 and III.12-13).  The poet, as though apologizing for what he is putting Virgil \softline
through in these scenes, reminds the reader of his enduring debt to the pagan poet, without whom \softline
this journey through the afterworld would have been impossible.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The word 'ragione' in verse 3 does not mean 'reason' but 'justice,' as is attested by Dante's \softline
earlier usage in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (where it nine times refers to law, especially Justinian's codification of \softline
Roman statutes -- see Vasoli's analytical index to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Il Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , in Dante Alighieri, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Opere \softline
minori}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , vol. I, part ii (Milan: Ricciardi, 1988)], pp. 1011-12), and the entire commentary tradition \softline
(even if a small subset of commentators believes the word here means 'conscience').  See also \softline
Marta Cristiani, 'ragione' (ED.1973.4), pp. 831-41, esp. p. 841.  In this context it nearly certainly \softline
refers to divine justice.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's remorse is self-caused.  As Venturi (comm. to verse 7) remarked, Virgil \softline
rebukes himself even though he could not have been a target of Cato's anger, since he was not a \softline
soul on the way to purgation.  And thus the little fault applies to him alone, not to Dante and the \softline
others (for all of whom it is considerably more serious).  Still, the attribution of the fault continues \softline
to cause a certain confusion.  A fairly typical understanding, with an allegorizing bent, is found in \softline
Di Benedetto ("Simboli e moralit{\f3 \'42} nel II canto del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Giornale storico della letteratura \softline
italiana}{\plain \fs24 \f1  162 [1985]), pp. 179-80: 'The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 picciol fallo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is that of Virgil, who stands for Reason and \softline
thus for Dante himself....  The "trivial fault" is assigned to Dante and the other souls.'  Pasquazi \softline
("Catone," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Cultura e scuola}{\plain \fs24 \f1  13-14 [1965]), p. 538, on the other hand, sees the phrase as referring \softline
to Virgil and not the others.  Levitan ("Dante as Listener, Cato's Rebuke, and Virgil's Self-Reproach," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  103 [1985]), pp. 50-54, also notes the differing nature of the guilt \softline
afflicting Virgil, whose drama is not one of potential salvation, from that of Dante (and the other \softline
Christian souls, one is tempted to add).  In this vein see also Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New \softline
Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis [virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990]), p. 40.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 10-11.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The image of Virgil looking somewhat foolish because he is running is the sort of \softline
detail one would expect to find in no other medieval poem.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Virgil, here momentarily lacking }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 onestade}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (dignity), is bracketed by the figures of Cato \softline
and the group containing Manfred; both of these are referred to as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 onesto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.119; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
III.87).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 12-13.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As Virgil is preoccupied with his minor failing, so Dante is troubled by his own \softline
guilty thoughts.  Daniello (comm. to verse 12) points to Cato's rebuke (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.120-121) as the \softline
cause of his shame when he considers his hesitation in moving toward the necessary mountain.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 dislagarsi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (literally meaning 'to unlake itself') is a Dantean coinage, a \softline
phenomenon that will grow as the poem progresses and flower in profusion in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 16-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's presence here in the body is a double-edged proposition, as it both \softline
emphasizes his extraordinary state of grace in being here in the flesh and his debilitated status, 
resulting from his fleshly view of things.  For a study of this phenomenon and its development \softline
through the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Philip Berk ("Shadows on the Mount of Purgatory," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  97 \softline
[1979], pp. 47-63), who points out that, while we may feel that Dante in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  all too \softline
frequently presents himself as casting a shadow, he in fact does so only six times: here; later in this \softline
canto (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.88-90); then in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.4-6, V.25-27, XXVI.4-8; XXVII.64-69.  Berk also \softline
makes the point that Dante's corporeal shadow finds a correspondence, later in the canto, in \softline
Manfred's wounds (vv. 108, 111), the signs of that soul's former mortality.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19-21.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Having noted his own shadow, the protagonist now is struck by the absence of \softline
Virgil's, and momentarily thinks he has been abandoned by his guide.  While, as soon as the \softline
travelers reached the shore of the mount of purgatory and reentered the sunlight, the protagonist \softline
might have noted that none of the immortal denizens of this new place casts a shadow -- not Cato, \softline
none of the pilgrims, not his guide -- the poet reserves that recognition for this canto, so filled \softline
with reminiscence of the death of Virgil.  \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 22-24.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Benvenuto da Imola's paraphrase of Virgil's rebuke begins with the words \softline
'modicae fidei': ('}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 you of little faith}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , why have you so easily lost the faith and the hope that you \softline
ought and may have in me, who never left you behind in the city of the demons?').  Benvenuto is \softline
clearly thinking of the words of Christ in the Gospels (in the Latin Bible the phrase 'modicae fidei' \softline
is found four times and only in Matthew [6:30; 8:26; 14:31; 16:8]).  If Benvenuto has correctly \softline
heard that echo, its effect is noteworthy, for then the faithless Virgil is reproving his pupil, \softline
modeling his speech on the words of Christ, for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 his}{\plain \fs24 \f1  lack of faith, evident on occasion from the \softline
first canto of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  until Virgil leaves the poem in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXX.  Whether Virgil is \softline
citing Scripture or having Scripture placed in his mouth by his Christian author is a problem the \softline
reader has already encountered (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VIII.45 and the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VIII.40-45).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 25-26.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Since it is shortly after dawn here in purgatory, it is shortly after sunset at the \softline
antipodes, Jerusalem.  And since Italy, in Dante's geography, lies midway between Jerusalem and \softline
Gibraltar, it is sometime after 3pm there, as evening (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 vespero}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) begins with the sun's last quarter, \softline
between 3pm and 6pm.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 27.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil died on 21 September 19 B.C. at Brindisi, a city in Apulia that still serves as a \softline
port for maritime travelers to and from Greece.  Augustus was responsible for the transfer of his \softline
body from Brindisi to Naples, or actually, Pozzuoli, some ten miles distant, where it was interred \softline
in a grotto in the vast tunnel, built by the ancient Romans, connecting Pozzuoli and the road to \softline
Naples.  John of Serravalle (comm. to vv. 25-27) records his having visited the site on 30 August \softline
1413 and having held bones of Virgil in his hands.  This passage begins what has been called 'an \softline
antepurgatorial preoccupation with the body and its place of burial' (by Denise Heilbronn, \softline
"Dante's Valley of the Princes," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  90 [1972], p. 44).  Selene Sarteschi ("Riflessioni \softline
sul canto di Manfredi," in her }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Per la "Commedia" e non per essa soltanto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Rome: Bulzoni, 2002 \softline
(1999)]), p. 246n., points out that the four presences of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 corpo}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in this canto represent the \softline
word's greatest frequency in any canto of the poem, thus underlining the importance of corporeal \softline
concerns with respect to Virgil, Dante, and Manfred.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Pietro di Dante (Pietro1, comm. to vv. 25-27) was perhaps the first to cite Virgil's \softline
versified epitaph, as found in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vitae}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of Virgil by Suetonius and Donatus:\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab \ul0 \tab Mantua me genuit, Calabri rapuere, tenet nunc\par
}\pard \fs24\fi-1440\li1440\tx720\tx1440 
