}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 In this experimental formulation Dante would, in exactly one hundred lines, have deployed the \softline
three 'spokes' of the stylistic }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 rota Vergilii}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (the wheel of Virgil).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Carroll (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.19-33) cites Plumptre for the opinion that this scene reflects \softline
the (unverified) tradition that St. Paul visited Virgil's grave at Naples and wept for the great poet, \softline
whom, had he but known him, he might have led to salvation.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 28-30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's heavens include the nine celestial spheres containing the Moon and, as \softline
they move higher, eventually no stellar bodies of any kind (the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Primum mobile}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  In }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  we \softline
will learn that, while they are material, they are also translucent.  Something similar is also the \softline
case with respect to the shades here.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil here touches on the nature of the 'aerial bodies' of the dead in hell and \softline
purgatory.  The Roman poet Statius will elaborate on the 'physical' nature of shades in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XXV.34-108.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-36.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The 'posthumous Christian' ruefully acknowledges, by pointing to reason as his \softline
means for attempting to know the essence of things, his failure to have had faith.  The reference to \softline
reason does not indicate, as some commentators insist, that Virgil embodies or personifies \softline
Reason, especially since, in this context, Reason would then be commenting on the shortcomings \softline
of reason.   Reason is a property (or, in Scholastic terms, an 'accident') of the Roman poet, not his \softline
essence.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 37.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 quia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is a term deriving from Scholastic discourse.  Benvenuto da Imola's \softline
paraphrase (comm. to vv. 37-39) nicely conveys both that style and precisely what is meant here: \softline
'sufficiat vobis credere quia sic est, et non quaerere propter quid est' (let it suffice you to believe \softline
that something is so, without seeking to know why it is so), i.e., to accept things as they are, \softline
without attempting to understand their causes.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 38-39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Some commentators (e.g., Benvenuto) are of the opinion that these lines indicate \softline
that had humankind been able to know the final mysteries, Adam and Eve would not have fallen \softline
and Christ would not have been needed to save us.  It seems far more likely that Dante's thought 
is more logically connected than such an analysis would indicate: had we known all, there would \softline
have been no need for Christ to come to bring us the final truth of things.  The focus here is not \softline
moral so much as it is intellectual.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 40-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Perhaps there is no passage in the poem that more clearly delineates the tragedy of \softline
Virgil, now studied by its protagonist himself.  His own fourth }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Eclogue}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , which spoke of a virgin \softline
who would give birth to a son, but did not mean Mary and did not mean Jesus, is symptomatic of \softline
how near he came and thus how great was his failure, a result here addressed in an unspoken \softline
gesture -- his lowering his head -- that swells with unshed tears.  In the last canto, the newly \softline
arrived pilgrims looked up with hope ('la nova gente }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alz{\f3 \'62} la fronte}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ' [the new people raised their \softline
faces]).  The words describing Virgil's silence echo key words from that passage in a contrastive \softline
spirit (as noted by Hollander, "}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II: The New Song and the Old," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis \softline
[virginiana]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  6 [1990], p. 36): 'e qui }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 chin{\f3 \'62} la fronte}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , / e pi{\f3 \'6a} non disse, e rimase turbato' [and here \softline
he lowered his brow, said nothing more, and seemed disturbed].  As Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 43-45) would have it, it is as though Virgil were saying: 'And woe is me, I was among their number.'\par
