}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 One way leads up through faith to Christian truth, mediated by the mortal woman who gave birth \softline
to God in the flesh, the other down from this potential happiness, through rational attempts to \softline
know the rationally unknowable, to everlasting unhappiness.  Mary and Plato are here the very \softline
emblems of the choices that we humans face.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-48.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   There is a sharp dividing line between the elegiac passage devoted to Virgil's \softline
consideration of his failure (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.22-45) and the scene that begins here, with the description \softline
of the sheer wall of the mountain and the first attempt at an ascent.  For an appreciation of the \softline
nonetheless unitary nature of this canto as a whole, see Walther Binni ("Lettura del canto III del \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Ancora con Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Ravenna: Longo, 1983 (1955)]), p. 9.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 49-51.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Lerici and Turbia are settlements at either end of the Ligurian coast, to either side \softline
of Genoa, a region marked by rugged mountains sloping to the sea and, in Dante's roadless day, \softline
difficult of access.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 52-57.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's question and attitude reveal a guide who has not taken }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 this}{\plain \fs24 \f1  trip previously, \softline
as he had in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  Further, while he falls back on the resource of his reason, the futility of \softline
which in certain situations has just been explored by the guide himself, his pupil, like the arriving \softline
penitents in the last canto (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.40-45), does the intuitive and hopeful thing: \softline
he looks up.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 58-60.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Having begun their attempt to ascend, Virgil and Dante begin moving leftward out \softline
of habit, we must assume.  (They will only learn what direction they should be moving in at verse \softline
101.)  Our first glimpse of the souls of ante-purgatory marks them as unexcited and slow-moving, 
attributes that will gain in meaning when we learn more about them.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For helpful references to Classical discussions of the morally charged nature of the \softline
directions of human movement (right, up, and ahead are all 'good'; left, down, and behind are all \softline
'bad') see Giorgio Stabile ("Cosmologia e teologia nella }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : la caduta di Lucifero e il \softline
rovesciamento del mondo," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Letture classensi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  12 [1983]), pp. 145-49.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 \ul0 \tab Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is traditionally divided into three areas: ante-purgatorio, made up of two major \softline
zones, Excommunication and Late Repentance (the latter divided into three sub-divisions, \softline
containing those dying unabsolved, those marked by negligence, and those who loved the world \softline
too much); purgatorio itself (divided into seven terraces, each of which represents one of the \softline
Seven Capital Vices), and the earthly paradise at the summit of the mountain.  (These divisions \softline
and the first naming of 'ante-purgatory' are found in Benvenuto [introductory note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I].)  \softline
Thus, like }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno }{\plain \fs24 \f1 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is divided into ten large 'parts' (in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  Neutrality, \softline
lack of faith (Limbo), Lust, Gluttony, Avarice, Anger, Heresy, Violence, Fraud, Treachery; in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  the nine heavens and the Empyrean).  However, for another view of the divisions of \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , see Victoria Kirkham ("I quindici gradi del regno di Catone," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Letteratura italiana \softline
e arti figurative}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : Atti del XII Convegno dell'Associazione Internazionale per gli Studi di Lingua e \softline
Letteratura Italiana [Toronto, Hamilton, Montreal, 6-10 maggio 1985], ed. Antonio Franceschetti \softline
[Florence: Olschki, 1988], vol. I, pp. 229-36).  Arguing from the Christian numerological \softline
tradition that makes fifteen the number of the spiritual ascent to God, she attempts to demonstrate \softline
that the second }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is meaningfully divided into fifteen 'steps.'  Her argument depends on an \softline
accountancy that may not seem convincing: there are four kinds of negligence, three kinds of \softline
pride, and, among the final six terraces, two that are 'double' (avarice and prodigality; \softline
heterosexual and homosexual lust), thus yielding a total of fifteen.  Further, one might object that \softline
this numbering omits both the first and last destinations of the penitent saved soul, 'pre-ante-purgatory,' where such as Casella await the journey to the antipodes (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.94-105), and the \softline
earthly paradise (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVIII-XXXIII), which for Kirkham obviously serves as destination \softline
rather than stage on the way to spiritual awareness, which is, however, surely to be found in the \softline
Empyrean, not in the earthly paradise itself.  One probably ends up wondering whether Dante's \softline
text itself invites his reader to enumerate the parts of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in this way.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 61-63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Underlining the difference between the guide's and the protagonist's ways of \softline
proceeding, Dante's remark, urging Virgil to look up, intrinsically reveals a reversal of roles, as \softline
was noted by Margherita Frankel ("La similitudine della zara [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040 . VI, 1-12] ed il rapporto fra \softline
