}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 72.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The souls are puzzled by what they see, two figures moving in the wrong direction (to \softline
the left) on this holy mountain, as Benvenuto da Imola was perhaps first to suggest.  Not only are \softline
they going in the wrong direction, they are also moving quickly, not at the reverential and \softline
thoughtful pace of penitence.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 73-78.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Virgil's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 captatio benevolentiae}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (the attempt to capture the goodwill of one's \softline
auditors) here, like the one he addressed to Cato in the first canto (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.70-84), reveals, as 
