simile, contrasting the humility exemplified here in Manfred (whom we shall soon come to \softline
understand is the 'bellwether' in the simile), whose life was marked by the opposite vice, \softline
presumption, in his opposition to the Church.  In one of his typical outbursts against his \softline
intellectual enemies in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Dante calls them stupid and compares them to sheep (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
I.xi.9-10), those sheep that follow their leader in jumping into a ravine a mile deep (is that \softline
phrasing, 'mille passi,' remembered in the same phrase at verse 68, above?  Frankel ["La \softline
similitudine della zara (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040 . VI, 1-12) ed il rapporto fra Dante e Virgilio nell'Antepurgatorio," in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1\lang1040 Studi Americani su Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1\lang1040 , ed. G. C. Alessio and R. Hollander (Milan: F. Angeli, 1989)], p. 124, \softline
is of that opinion).  Citation of this passage in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  was perhaps first brought into play by \softline
