}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 103-105.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Manfred died (February 1266) some eight or nine months after Dante was born.  \softline
His question is thus groundless, notwithstanding the exertions of commentators like Tommaseo \softline
(comm. to these verses), Andreoli (comm. to verse 105), and Poletto (to these verses) who argue \softline
that Dante, as a deeply thoughtful man, looked old for his age.  The utterly human perception that \softline
lies behind the poet's lending Manfred this question is that the great and famous are used to being \softline
recognized, and often assume that everybody has seen them, even if they themselves tend to have \softline
small recollection of the many whom they have encountered.  On the other hand, his question may \softline
also be a hopeful one, i.e., if this living soul happens to recognize him, Manfred hopes that he will \softline
cause others to pray for him -- see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.49-50, where other late-repentant souls make \softline
similar requests.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 107-108.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The 'realism' of the detail of this scarred eyebrow has drawn much admiration.  \softline
Singleton's comment (comm. to this verse) cites Augustine, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 De civ. Dei}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXII.xix.3: 'For, in the \softline
martyrs, such wounds will not be a deformity; they will have a dignity and loveliness all their own; \softline
and, though this radiance will be spiritual and not physical, it will, in some way, beam from their \softline
bodies.'  He goes on to suggest that Manfred, though excommunicated by the Church, nonetheless \softline
is treated here as a sort of martyr, 'persecuted' by that very Church.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Having once seen John Fitzgerald Kennedy standing in a convertible moving up Fifth \softline
Avenue on a magnificent sun-filled autumn afternoon in October of 1960, shortly before he was \softline
elected president of his country, his shock of red-blond hair dazzling in the sunlight, the writer \softline
cannot read this passage without remembering that other handsome, womanizing, self-confident \softline
leader who would also die wounded in the head.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For a Biblical passage that Dante possibly had in mind as he described Manfred, see \softline
Grandgent (comm. to verse 107): 'Cf. 1 Samuel 16:12: "Now he [David] was ruddy, and withal of \softline
a beautiful countenance and goodly to look at.'''  Manfred's resemblance to David has been \softline
reasserted by various later commentators.  Bosco/Reggio (comm. to vv. 106-120) add a similar \softline
description of Roland in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Chanson de Roland}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (verse 2278: 'Bels fut e forz e de grant \softline
vasselage').  John Freccero (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante: The Poetics of Conversion}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Rachel Jacoff [Cambridge: \softline
Harvard University Press, 1986]), pp. 206-7, sees a resemblance to the similarly handsome and ill-fated Marcellus (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.860-885).  However, the literal context does not seem to support this \softline
analogy and it may be more appropriate to consider another Virgilian antecedent to Manfred, the \softline
tragic figure of Deiphobus (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.495-499), who attempts to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 hide}{\plain \fs24 \f1  his wounds from Aeneas, his \softline
mangled ears and his nose ('truncas inhonesto volnere naris' [his nostrils laid bare by a shameful 
wound -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.498]).  Deiphobus, desiring }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 not}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to be recognized by his wounds, is, in this \softline
understanding, a foil to Manfred, eager to display the wound in his chest.  Perhaps the first \softline
commentator to note this correspondence was Mattalia (comm. to verse 111); and see Hollander \softline
("Dante's 'Georgic' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIV, 1-18]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  102 [1984]), p. 119. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 111.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Manfred's second wound (the poet will insist on the importance of the fact that he \softline
has }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 two}{\plain \fs24 \f1  visible wounds in verse 119), perhaps reminiscent of the wound in Christ's side (John \softline
19:34; 20:25), causes the reader to consider the possible significances of these two marks on his \softline
body.  Perhaps we are to understand that the first wound, in his brow, traditionally and in Dante \softline
the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 locus}{\plain \fs24 \f1  of pride (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.45 and the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.45; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIV.35 and the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXXIV.35), is the sign of his pride brought low, his mark of Cain, as it were, now made good in \softline
his gesture of revealing his other wound, his mark of Christ, the seal of his humility.  Torraca \softline
(comm. to vv. 109-111) is nearly alone in seeing the resemblance, antithetic though it be, between \softline
the gestures of self-revelation in displaying wounds found in Manfred here and in Mohammed \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVIII.29-31); and see the similar appreciation in Denise Heilbronn ("Dante's Valley of the \softline
Princes," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  90 [1972]), p. 43.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 112.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Manfred's smile is part of a 'program' of smiling found in the two final }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantiche}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (see \softline
the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.83).  His way of naming himself seems to be part of a program limited to the \softline
ante-purgatory, the only part of the poem in which characters name themselves using this formula \softline
('io son' followed by their own name).  Manfred's smiling self-identification stands out from the \softline
evasive behavior in this regard exhibited by most of the sinners in hell.  For the others who \softline
employ this formula see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.88 (Buonconte da Montefeltro), }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.34 \softline
(Sordello), }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VII.7 (Virgil).  In the less personal exchanges in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  only St. \softline
Bonaventure uses a version of it: 'Io son la vita di Bonaventura...' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII.127).  There the great \softline
Franciscan identifies himself as a living heavenly soul.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Born ca. 1231, Manfred was the illegitimate son of the emperor Frederick II and Bianca \softline
Lancia, and thus the natural grandson of Emperor Henry VI and Constance of Sicily.  He was also \softline
the father, by his wife Beatrice of Savoy, of Constance, who married King Peter III of Aragon \softline
(see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.115-116).  When Frederick died in 1250, Manfred was appointed regent of Sicily in \softline
the absence of his brother, Conrad IV, involved elsewhere.  When Conrad died, in 1254, leaving \softline
the realm to his three-year-old son, Conradin, Manfred again became regent.  At the rumors of the \softline
child's death, in 1258 (he would in fact survive another ten years), Manfred was crowned king in \softline
Palermo.  This did not sit well with the pope, and Alexander IV excommunicated him in 1258, as \softline
did Urban IV in 1261.  Urban offered the vacated forfeited crown to Louis IX of France who, \softline
refusing it, opened the path to an invitation of Charles of Anjou, who accepted.  Once Charles \softline
was crowned in Rome in January 1266, he set out to destroy Manfred, an aim that he \softline
accomplished the next month at the battle of Benevento.  A lover of the 'good life' at court, a \softline
fervent Ghibelline, a man charged (whether correctly or not) with a number of murders of his \softline
cofamiliars, supposedly undertaken to advance his political hopes, Manfred was not, at least not in \softline
Guelph eyes, a selection for salvation that could have been calculated to win sympathy to the \softline
work that contained such news.  It is at least reasonable to believe that the first damned soul we \softline
see in hell is Celestine V (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.58-60), a pope of saintly habits; here the first soul \softline
we find saved on the mountain is the excommunicated Manfred.  Whatever else Dante enjoyed \softline
doing as he wrote this poem, he clearly delighted in shocking his readers -- as though the salvation 
of Cato, with which the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  begins, were not incredible enough for us.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab On the problems raised for commentators by the salvation of the excommunicated \softline
Manfred see Louis La Favia ("Per una reinterpretazione dell'episodio di Manfredi," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
91 [1973]), who points out that a letter of Pope Innocent III dating from 1199 fully supports the \softline
notion that an excommunicate can eventually be saved, a position, as he demonstrates, that was \softline
not nearly as shocking to Dante's earliest readers as it would later become.  La Favia produces the \softline
key portion of that Latin text (pp. 87-88).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 113.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Manfred does not identify himself as his father's son (Frederick II is, after all, \softline
condemned to hell for heresy: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . X.119) but by reference to his paternal grandmother, \softline
Constance  (1154-98), daughter of Roger II, king of Sicily, and wife of Emperor Henry VI, by \softline
whom she became the mother of Frederick.  As Benvenuto uniquely (among the early \softline
commentators) points out, Dante has borrowed this tactic from Polynices who, questioned about \softline
his lineage by the king of Argos, Adrastus, in Statius's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Thebaid}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , prefers to omit the name of \softline
Oedipus in favor of that of his mother, Jocasta (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Theb}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.676-681).  Porena (comm. to vv. 112-113) notes that Dante himself had remembered this scene in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.xxx.10), laying \softline
the avoidance on Polynices' part both to his desire to omit reference to his own harsh actions \softline
against his father as well as to keep concealed Oedipus's evil deeds.  Hermann Gmelin \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Kommentar: der L{\f2\u228\'e4}uterungsberg}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Stuttgart: Klett, 1955]), p. 79, offers further discussion.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 117.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The poet's self-awareness is unmistakable here.  Hardly anyone in his time would \softline
have consented to the notion that Manfred had been saved.  He places this reference to the \softline
imagined dubiety of those who might hear such news (i.e., by reading Dante's poem) in the mouth \softline
of his character and it is our turn to smile.  Yet we can imagine how many Guelphs and \softline
churchmen would have fumed at this passage, adamant in their vehement and unflagging belief \softline
that Manfred had been damned.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 121-123.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The sinners in hell, we must assume, failed exactly to do, even at the last \softline
moment of their lives, what Manfred did.  While he is held back from purgation for the \softline
insubordination that resulted in his excommunication, he, too, is a late-repentant saved soul.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 124-129.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The archbishop of Cosenza, in Calabria, enlisted by Pope Clement IV in his \softline
battles against Manfred's Ghibellines, was responsible, at the end, for disinterring his corpse, \softline
buried under the cairn of stones piled upon his body by Guelph troops after the battle of \softline
Benevento.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab There is some dispute as to the precise meaning of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 faccia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  here.  Does it mean \softline
'face' or 'page'?  For the former, see Freccero (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante: The Poetics of Conversion}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Rachel \softline
Jacoff [Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1986]), p. 206.  For 'faccia' as page, see Frankel \softline
("Dante's Anti-Virgilian }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 villanello}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  102 [1984]), p. 107.  The page in God's \softline
writing indicated here is perhaps found at Revelation 20:12, the reference to the Book of Life, in \softline
which are recorded the names of the saved, including, we must reflect, that of Manfred.  Further, \softline
three particulars lend support to those who argue for 'page,' }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 faccia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as an apocopation of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 facciata}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : \softline
(1) While most of the early commentators are vague in their readings of this verse, those who \softline
wrote in the Renaissance and after tend to find this interpretation more natural; (2) modern \softline
commentators mainly prefer 'face,' if without the sort of convincing argument that might conclude 
