the notes to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  V.91-93 and VI.28-33.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 131-135.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Adding insult to the injury of disinterment, the archbishop ordered Manfred's \softline
remains to be cast back into the world.  They had first at least been allowed burial in \softline
unconsecrated ground with the ceremony prescribed for the excommunicate ('with torches \softline
quenched').  And so the corpse is put out of the Kingdom of Naples and Sicily onto a bank of the \softline
river Verde, today the Liri.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The name of the river,}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Verde}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (green), however, stands intrinsically opposed to such \softline
purpose, since it both traditionally represents the virtue of hope and happens to have been the \softline
color that Manfred himself favored.  And thus the identical rhyme 'Verde/verde' underlines the \softline
hopeful sign that Manfred's faith believed would come and his love longed for.  The Church's \softline
human agents may not understand God's hidden disposition.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The final phrase here, 'ha fior del verde,' has caused much difficulty.  Lombardi (comm. to \softline
verse 135) paraphrases the passage as follows: 'so long as death does not entirely dry up hope, but \softline
leaves a single thread of it green.'  The spirit of comedy in this canto overcomes the atmosphere of \softline
tragedy.  We might reflect that this is the first true narrative of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (neither Cato nor \softline
Casella gives the sort of perfectly formed autobiographical performance to which we have become \softline
accustomed in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  The first }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  has trained us to expect "tragedy," the tale told, from \softline
the sinner's point of view, of death and damnation.  Unconsciously, we may expect exactly that \softline
sort of narrative here.  And it surely seems to be similar, with its story of horrific death and \softline
undignified burial; yet here we find the tragic surmounted by the comic resolution offered by \softline
redemption.  Thus Manfred's narrative is set as a pattern for all those we shall hear in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatory}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  \softline
For a discussion of Manfred's narrative as tragic in tone and comic in result, see Selene Sarteschi \softline
("Riflessioni sul canto di Manfredi," in her }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Per la "Commedia" e non per essa soltanto}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Rome: \softline
Bulzoni, 2002 (1999)]), p. 237.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 139.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For a possible precursor for this period of delay, see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.325-30, the one \softline
hundred years of wandering exacted of the souls of the unburied dead before they are permitted to \softline
cross Acheron, a connection perhaps first suggested by Daniello (comm. to vv. 136-141).  But \softline
this does not explain Dante's choice of the number thirty.  It is not until the twentieth century that \softline
one finds a commentator wondering about the possible reasons for this choice: Grandgent (comm. \softline
to this verse): {\u8219\'27}Why thirty?  See E. G. Gardner in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Modern Language Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , IX, 63.  In \softline
